*** The following steps describe setting up the Report to AbuseIPDB for Splunk app on a CentOS 7 server. If you
    are using a Debian based server please refer to the DEBIAN NOTE at the bottom of this document.

Step 1)  Configure a Splunk® forwarder to monitor the /var/log directory.

Step 2)  Configure a Splunk® receiver to accept data from the port you configured the forwarder to send data to.

Step 3)  Click on the “Report to Abuseipdb for Splunk” app icon and verify that there is a flow of data by clicking
	 on the Data Summary button.

	*Note* During testing, we noticed that following the documentation for configuring a forwarder through CLI
	 caused a “TailReader Error”.  At this point, Splunk was not receiving data either. The issue was resolved
 	 by Going to Settings>Forwarding and Receiving and deleting both the forwarder and receiver.

Step 4)  Once the data is flowing in, the next step is to add your AbuseIPDB APIv2 key to the alert_actions.conf
         file. This file is located in /opt/splunk/etc/apps/abuseipdb/default

 	 Locate the line: # Enter your AbuseIPDB APIv2 key below.
	 Under that line, there should be param.key = Paste your API key to the right of the equal sign then save
	 the file.

	 If you do not have an Abuseipdb Key, you can create one by going to
 		https://www.abuseipdb.com/account/api and clicking Create Key.

	 If you do not have an Abuseipdb account, the API is free to use, but you have to create an account at
		https://www.abuseipdb.com/register

Step 5)  From /opt/splunk/etc/apps/abuseipdb/default open the savedsearches.conf file and locate the following
	 line under the [Messages Log Report] stanza:
		search = host=YOUR_HOST_NAME "SRC=*" SRC!="YOUR_IP_HERE”
		source="/var/log/messages”

	 Replace YOUR_HOST_NAME with the host name of your server, and YOUR_IP_HERE with your IP. You can exclude
	 other IPs you would not like reported in the same manner by adding “ SRC!="YOUR_IP_HERE” again to this line.

Step 6)  Locate the following line under the [Secure Log Report] stanza:
		search = host=YOUR_HOST_NAME  source="/var/log/secure" ip="*" NOT "YOUR_IP_HERE”

	 Replace YOUR_HOST_NAME with the host name of your server, and YOUR_IP_HERE with your IP. You can exclude
	 other IPs you would not like reported in the same manner by adding NOT “YOUR_IP_HERE” or
	 ip!= “YOUR_IP_HERE”  again to this line and save the file.

Step 7)  Move to the data/models directory.

	 Locate the following line in Messages_Alert.json:
		"search": "host=YOUR_HOSTNAME \"SRC=*\" SRC!=\"YOUR_IP_HERE$

	 Replace YOUR_HOST_NAME with the host name of your server, and YOUR_IP_HERE with your IP. You can exclude
	 other IPs you would not like reported in the same manner by adding SRC!="YOUR_IP_HERE” again to this line
	 and save the file.

Step 8)  From the data/models directory, Locate the following line in Secure_Alert.json:
		"search": "host=YOUR_HOST_NAME  source=\"/var/log/secure\" ip=\"*\" NOT \"YOUR_IP_HERE\""

	 Replace YOUR_HOST_NAME with the host name of your server, and YOUR_IP_HERE with your IP. You can exclude
	 other IPs you would not like reported in the same manner by adding NOT “YOUR_IP_HERE” or
	 ip!= “YOUR_IP_HERE”  again to this line and save the file.

Step 9) From /opt/splunk/etc/apps/abuseipdb/bin, open report.py. On line 32, replace the words "YOUR_IP_HERE" with the IP of your server, or any IPs that you would like to not be reported.

Step 10)  Navigate to the /opt/splunk/bin directory and restart splunk by entering:
		./splunk restart into the terminal

Step 11) Verify that everything is working properly:
    	     1. Check the AbuseIPDB dashboard and verify that it is showing data
    	     2. Check that the alerts are triggering when they are supposed to:
        	   a. The secure log alert triggers anytime there is an invalid/failed login attempt recorded to the
		   secure log file.
        	   b. The messages log alert triggers anytime the kernel blocks an incoming IP with the firewall
		        **If you messages log does not currently have any port scanning data, there will not be a
			  SRC field and therefor no results for this search. The search and alert will begin working
			  on their own once this data is introduced.
        	   c. Both of these alerts will appear in the Activity>Triggered Alerts tab of Splunk® Web
    	     3. Ensure that the report script is running properly by monitoring your AbuseIPDB report page at
		https://www.abuseipdb.com/account/reports
        	   a. If successful, each time a log event occurs on either /var/log/messages or /var/log/secure
		      there should be a report logged to your account on our website.
        	   b. If reports are not showing up, but your alerts are triggering, make sure you added your API
		      Key to the alert_action.conf file

*****Optional - Steps for creating your own custom alert to report to AbuseIPDB*****

Step 1)  Determine which log file you would like to monitor

	 In the Report to AbuseIPDB for Splunk search bar type: source="PATH_TO_YOUR_LOG_FILE" and run your search

Step 2)  Check the list of Fields located on the left of your search results. If you see an ip or SRC field continue
	 to step 3.

	 If you do not see one of these two fields you will need to extract your own by following these steps:
             1. Click extract new fields
	     2. Select a sample event by clicking a line in your search results and then clicking next
	        on the progress bar at the top of the page.
     	     3. Click I prefer to write the Regular Expression myself.
	     4. Enter the following regex and click preview:
	           (?<ip>\d+\.\d+\.\d+\.\d+)  **This is for IPv4. If you need IPv6 you will need to modify it.
	     5. Click Save to continue to next step.
	     6. Set permissions to app, everyone can read and admin can write
	     7. Ensure that the extraction name is ip and then click finish

Step 3)  Find and click either the ip or SRC field and then click events with this field

Step 4)  In the search bar following the existing search type NOT "YOUR_IP_HERE" making sure to fill in your ip
	 address and then run the search

Step 5)  Click Save As then select Alert

Step 6)  Enter a title and description of your choosing and enter an expiration that suits your needs

Step 7)  Set permissions to Shared in App

Step 8)  Set Alert type to Real Time

Step 9)  Make sure that the trigger alert when setting is per-result

Step 10) Under trigger actions click add actions and then click Add to triggered alerts with a severity of your
	 choosing.

	 Click add actions again and click the report action which has the AbuseIPDB logo with a category and
	 comment of your choosing - please make the comment relateable to the type of attack and click save

Step 11) In the directory /opt/splunk/etc/apps/abuseipdb/bin open the file report.py so that you can edit it

Step 12) **The following code will be inserted directly above the initialization of the url variable**

	 elif data["result"]["source"] == PATH_TO_YOUR_FILE:
       	      logfile = A_FILE_OF_YOUR_CHOOSING_TO_RECORD_SERVER_RESPONSE
              ip = data["result"]["NAME_OF_YOUR_IP_FIELD_IN_ALERT"]

	 Replace your file names before saving the code

Step 13) Restart Splunk by going to /opt/splunk/bin and running ./splunk restart


*****DEBIAN NOTE*****

Due to a diffent file naming system you will need to update your file paths.

Anywhere that we use /var/log/secure your will need to replace it with /var/log/auth.log
Anywhere that we use /var/log/messages you will need to replace it with /var/log/syslog

Files where you will need to make these changes are:
	/opt/splunk/etc/apps/abuseipdb/default/savedsearchs.conf
	/opt/splunk/etc/apps/abuseipdb/default/data/models/Messages_Alert.json
	/opt/splunk/etc/apps/abuseipdb/default/data/models/Secure_Alert.json
	/opt/splunk/etc/apps/abuseipdb/bin/report.py
